Honeypot — Catch Hackers (Cybersecurity Project)
 README, Deliverables Checklist, Key Files
 Short description
 A modular honeypot lab that deploys lightweight, containerized honeypots (SSH, HTTP) to capture
 attacker activity, log events, and forward logs for analysis. Includes automation (Ansible) for deployment
 and GitHub Actions CI for safe updates.
 Goals- Deploy one or more honeypot services (SSH, HTTP) in isolated environment- Capture and store attacker logs and artifacts- Provide automated deployment and repeatable environment- Produce analysis-ready logs and alerts for SOC/learning
 Key components
 docker-compose.yml — Containerized honeypot services (e.g., Cowrie for SSH/Telnet, Glastopf for web)
 ansible/ — Playbook to provision a fresh Ubuntu host, install Docker and deploy containers
 collect/ — Log forwarding (Filebeat / logrotate) and simple Python analytics
 ci/ — GitHub Actions workflow to lint and optionally deploy
 docs/ — Notes, sample analysis, and ethics/legal checklist
 Quickstart (lab environment)
 1. Clone repo:
   git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/honeypot-catch-hackers.git
   cd honeypot-catch-hackers
 2. Copy and edit .env (example .env.sample included):
   cp .env.sample .env
   # edit ports, credentials, and alert webhook values
 3. Start locally (lab, VM, or isolated VPS):
   docker-compose up -d
 4. Verify containers:
   docker-compose ps
   docker logs -f cowrie
 5. (Optional) Deploy to remote host with Ansible:
   ansible-playbook -i inventory/hosts playbook.yml
 Supported honeypots (defaults included)
 Cowrie — SSH / Telnet honeypot (emulates shell, collects sessions)
 Glastopf — Web application honeypot (captures web attacks)
 Filebeat — forwards logs to collector (Elasticsearch / Graylog / local file)
 Architecture (simple)
 Internet -> Public IP -> NAT -> Honeypot VM (isolated VLAN)
  docker-compose:
    - cowrie (SSH honeypot) -> /data/cowrie/log
    - glastopf (HTTP honeypot) -> /data/glastopf/log
    - filebeat -> forwards logs -> SIEM/ELK/Graylog
  analysis:
    - python scripts parse logs -> generate alerts -> alert webhook/Slack
